We can solve this differential equation using the method of undetermined coefficients. Let's assume that the particular solution has the form $x_p(t) = At^2 + Bt + C$.

Then, we can substitute this into the differential equation and equate the coefficients:

\begin{align*}
\ddot{x}_p(t) - x_p(t) &= t^2 + t + 1 \\
2A - A t^2 + B - (At^2 + Bt + C) &= t^2 + t + 1 \\
(2A - A - A) t^2 + (B - B - C) t + (C - 1) &= 0 \\
(A - 1) t^2 + (-C) t + (C - 1) &= 0
\end{align*}

Since this equation must be an identity, we can equate the coefficients:

\begin{align*}
A - 1 &= 0 \\
-C &= 0 \\
C - 1 &= 1
\end{align*}

Solving for $A, B, C$, we get:

\begin{align*}
A &= 1 \\
B &= 0 \\
C &= 1
\end{align*}

So, the particular solution is:

\begin{align*}
x_p(t) &= At^2 + Bt + C \\
&= t^2 + 1
\end{align*}

The general solution is the sum of the particular solution and the homogeneous solution. The homogeneous solution is:

\begin{align*}
x_h(t) &= e^{rt} \\
&= c_1 e^{rt} + c_2 e^{-rt}
\end{align*}

where $r$ is the root of the characteristic equation:

\begin{align*}
r^2 - 1 &= 0 \\
r &= \pm 1
\end{align*}

So, the general solution is:

\begin{align*}
x(t) &= x_p(t) + x_h(t) \\
&= t^2 + 1 + c_1 e^t + c_2 e^{-t}
\end{align*}

